How long does coronavirus hang around on surfaces?Two studies released in the New England Journal of Medicine and The Lancet took a look at the coronavirus’s shelf life. After introducing it to various surfaces in a lab environment, researchers found that the virus remains infective for 24 hours on cardboard packages and less than three hours on printer or tissue paper. Smoother surfaces tended to harbor viral particles for much longer; three to four days on plastic and up to seven days on stainless steel and, alarmingly, surgical masks. Nice Laboratories shows just how to use their Nice Hand Sanitizer on your mask on their website. A few sprays on the outside and the inside, let it dry for at least 20 minutes. The makers of Nice Hand Sanitizer have other good info on their website www.TheNiceCorp.com that can also help around the house and in your car.The CDC says you’re less likely to become infected by surface transmission than by coming into contact with respiratory droplets, but disinfecting high-use surfaces, like doorknobs and kitchen counters, daily is still critical. Wipe these surfaces down with paper towels and a Sanitizer  spray.If you can’t find disinfectant, go to www.TheNiceCorp.com they have a very large inventory and can ship the same day in most cases.

I talked to a co-worker about what is going on in the USA right now. Yes, she is black. I asked questions and was very happy that she was straight with me.  I’m as white as you can be (blonde and blue eyed). I do know that the blacks deal with prejudice on a daily basis.  I don’t like the word racism.  I grew up in OC California and San Diego. A black family moved into the neighborhood I lived in (I was 10), I played with the boys in the family, I didn’t care I considered them my friend. The oldest boy went to the same elementary school as I did. Yes, I hung out with him at school!! Some boys in my class would bully him and start fights with him. I remember screaming at one of the boys to leave him alone, he’s nice and fun to hang out with. My family moved to San Diego for 5 years. The area we lived in was a military area. A variety of races lived there and no one cared. I had many friends. The schools that I went to in San Diego were very diverse and no one cared!! We got a long. I saw my first interracial couple in San Diego. This was in the early 70’s.  We moved back to OC and it hadn’t changed much.  I had started to read an article in Reader’s Digest, the woman wrote “all my life I felt that I was not raciest” she called her friend (black) and asked her how she was doing after what happened to George in MINNESOTA. Her friend replied to her that she was the 3rd person that called her to ask how she was doing. They started to have a long talk about their childhood. It was then that she realized that she had been prejudiced towards her friend not realizing what she was saying was prejudiced.  I wasn’t able too finish the article as I was reading it on my phone. I am 52 and very top heavy and in May, I asked my doctor why my breasts seem to be "growing" and I was told it's because I put on weight (mind you, my medical records show I had been gaining and losing the same 5-10 pounds for at least 2 years.) To appease me, I was sent for my annual mammogram screening. The amount of time that passed between the order for the test being placed to the time it took to finally get me on the schedule was 2 months (I was told the delay was because of COVID), but in that time, a lump appeared almost in the center of my chest. Initially, I was told that because it showed up so quickly, it was probably just a cyst. Well, I demanded to bypass additional tests and partial biopsies and went straight for surgical removal of the lump and I'm glad I did. It wasn't a cyst; it was a fast growing tumor (that wasn't there in January) and I have been diagnosed with triple negative breast cancer. This coming week, I will get my surgery and my chemo on the schedule and I am ready to fight with every ounce of strength God has given me. My point...if you feel something is wrong, don't let your doctors downplay your concerns. Get screened, demand action and get everyone on the same page with your health.
